==English==
===Noun Phrase===
'''[[false]] [[cognate]]''' (''plural'' '''false cognates''')

# A word that appears to be [[cognate]] - to have a shared linguistic origin to a given word, but is in fact unrelated.
# A [[false friend]] - a word that appears to have the same meaning as a given word, but does not. Some speakers consider this usage to be incorrect.

===Examples===
# The word for "dog" in the Australian Aboriginal language Mbabaram happens to be ''dog''.
# Many completely unrelated languages use some variant of ''ma'' for "mother".
# English ''have'' and Latin ''habere'' are thought to be false cognates (''have'' is more likely cognate to ''capere'').
# French ''attendre'' and English ''attend'' are cognates (shared root), but false friends (different meanings).  Thus, they are only false cognates in sense 2.

